  "findings": [
    {
      "dimension": "philosophy_depth",
      "score": 2,
      "finding": "All 6 principles are generic channel sales platitudes that could appear in any B2B sales textbook. 'Partner Success = Our Success' and 'Mutual Value Creation' are recycled industry clichés with no specificity to Story Portal's mission, partner types (festival networks, arts orgs), or the unique dynamics of selling an empathy-driven storytelling platform through indirect channels. None of the principles address the tension between commercial targets and mission alignment, the complexity of enabling non-sales-native arts partners, or the asymmetry in sophistication between tech partners and community groups.",
      "example_rewrite": "| Principle | Meaning |\n|-----------|--------|\n| **Mission-First Partner Selection** | A partner with 500 community touchpoints who shares our empathy mission outweighs a high-volume reseller who treats stories as transactions — filter for values alignment before revenue potential |\n| **Enable the Non-Seller** | Arts organizations and community groups are not sales teams; our enablement must teach storytelling value, not sales technique — meet partners where they are |\n| **Festival Presence as Proof** | Live event activation is our highest-trust channel; a festival network deal is worth 3x a digital referral agreement because it creates shared audience experience |\n| **Pipeline Transparency Over Optimism** | Report partner pipeline accurately to CRO even when uncomfortable — channel forecasts that inflate to protect relationships destroy planning credibility |\n| **Co-Sell or Don't Count It** | Partner-sourced opportunities only enter channel revenue when an AE is actively engaged — shadow pipeline inflates numbers and creates conflict with direct sales |\n| **Offboard Fast, Offboard Clean** | An inactive partner who holds exclusivity in a territory blocks mission-aligned alternatives — review cadence must include offboarding criteria, not just growth metrics |"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "handoff_specificity",
      "score": 4,
      "finding": "Handoff tables name roles but artifacts are vague labels, not actual documents. 'Channel strategy' from CRO could mean a slide deck, a quota memo, or a verbal direction. 'Partner opportunities' delivered to Sales Team gives no indication of format, minimum qualification criteria, or what stage a partner lead must reach before handoff. The 'Partnership Manager' appears in the Works With table and Boundaries section but is not in the Handoffs table at all — a notable gap given this role must coordinate with them on strategic alignment. 'Marketing' receives 'Partner insights' with no specification of format, cadence, or what threshold of data triggers the handoff.",
      "example_rewrite": "| Delivers To | Artifact | Format | Trigger |\n|-------------|----------|--------|---------|\n| CRO | Monthly Channel Performance Report | Standardized scorecard: partner count, pipeline by tier, revenue vs. target, health RAG status | Last business day of month |\n| Account Executive | Partner-Qualified Opportunity Brief | 1-page doc: partner name, contact, deal context, estimated ARR, co-sell ask, suggested next step | When partner identifies named prospect with confirmed budget signal |\n| Marketing | Partner Activation Insights | Quarterly summary: which partner types drove highest conversion, top objections heard in field, content gaps reported by partners | 15th of quarter-end month |\n| Partnership Manager | Strategic Partner Escalation Memo | Written escalation with partner background, commercial terms discussed, reason direct handling is insufficient | When inbound partner meets Strategic tier criteria per charter |"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "anti_pattern_quality",
      "score": 2,
      "finding": "The role has no dedicated Anti-Patterns section at all — what exists is a generic DO/DON'T boundary list that describes jurisdictional rules, not failure modes. The template standard explicitly requires 3-5 role-specific anti-patterns. The DON'T items ('Don't finalize contracts', 'Don't compete with direct sales') are basic boundary reminders, not behavioral failure patterns an AI or human would actually drift into. There is no warning about common Channel Partner Manager failure modes such as over-investing in low-performing partners, building shadow pipelines, or creating enablement content that duplicates Marketing's work.",
      "example_rewrite": "## Anti-Patterns\n\n| Anti-Pattern | What It Looks Like | Why It's Dangerous |\n|---|---|---|\n| **The Loyalty Trap** | Continuing to invest in an underperforming partner because of a strong personal relationship with their leader | Blocks territory for mission-aligned replacements; CRO sees channel revenue flatline while you report 'relationship health is strong' |\n| **Enablement Theater** | Delivering training sessions with high attendance scores but no measurable increase in partner-sourced pipeline | Creates the appearance of progress while partners still can't articulate Story Portal's value proposition in a sales conversation |\n| **Shadow Pipeline Inflation** | Logging partner 'expressions of interest' as pipeline before an AE has validated the opportunity | Causes direct sales conflicts when AEs discover 'their' prospects are already in channel pipeline; destroys CRO forecast accuracy |\n| **Content Duplication** | Building partner-facing sales decks and one-pagers independently because Marketing 'takes too long' | Creates version control chaos, off-brand materials in market, and erodes Marketing's ability to maintain consistent Story Portal messaging |\n| **Exclusivity Creep** | Granting informal territorial exclusivity to a partner during verbal negotiations before Legal reviews the agreement | Exposes Story Portal to unenforceable commitments that block future direct sales or competing partnerships in high-value markets |"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "ai_deployment_clarity",
      "score": 5,
      "finding": "The Iteration Protocol and Hybrid classification are present, which provides basic operational structure. However, the Context Requirements section is entirely unfilled — '[Context item 1]' and '[Context item 2]' are literal placeholders, and the Required Skills table has no entries. An AI agent loading this role has no idea what context files to pull, what data to request at session start, or what constitutes a complete information set before beginning work. The STOP points in workflows are present but lack specificity about what output is reviewed, by whom, and what approval looks like. An AI cannot distinguish between 'STOP → Plan ready' meaning 'save to CRM' vs. 'email to CRO for approval'.",
      "example_rewrite": "### Required Context\n- [ ] Current partner tier list with ARR and health status (from CRM export)\n- [ ] Active channel quota and attainment-to-date (from CRO or RevOps)\n- [ ] Partner program terms and tier thresholds document\n- [ ] Story Portal product positioning deck (latest version from Marketing)\n- [ ] Open co-sell opportunities in CRM assigned to channel\n- [ ] Last quarterly partner business review summaries\n\n### STOP Point Specification Example:\n'STOP → Plan ready' means: Onboarding plan document drafted with milestones, resource assignments, and 90-day revenue target. Human (Channel Partner Sales Manager) reviews and confirms before scheduling kickoff with partner contact. AI does not initiate partner communication until human confirms plan.'"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "story_portal_relevance",
      "score": 4,
      "finding": "The Story Portal appendix names the right partner categories (festival networks, arts organizations, community groups, technology partners) and gestures at mission alignment, but provides no actionable specificity. 'Mission alignment: Shared empathy goals' tells an AI nothing about how to evaluate a festival network partner vs. reject one. There are no partner qualification criteria, no example partner profiles, no indication of what a Story Portal channel deal actually looks like (revenue share? referral fee? co-branded content?), and no guidance on how festival-season timing affects the partner sales cycle. The priorities table lists 4 items with no rationale, metrics, or timelines.",
      "example_rewrite": "### Partner Qualification Criteria (Story Portal)\n\n| Partner Type | Minimum Threshold | Disqualifier |\n|---|---|---|\n| Festival Network | 500+ annual attendees, at least 1 storytelling or narrative-themed programming track | Commercial entertainment focus with no community/empathy programming |\n| Arts Organization | Active membership base with digital communication channel; mission references community or human connection | Purely transactional ticketing entity with no editorial voice |\n| Community Group | Established leader with 12+ months of programming history; geographic presence in a target Story Portal market | Informal group with no consistent audience or event cadence |\n| Technology Partner | API or embed capability confirmed; existing user base overlaps with Story Portal's target demographic | Competitor platform or tool that replicates core Story Portal narrative features |\n\n### Channel Deal Structure (Story Portal Standard)\n- Referral partners: 15% of first-year ARR on referred accounts\n- Co-sell partners: Joint pipeline sharing, AE introduction required within 5 business days of partner referral\n- Festival activation partners: In-kind Story Portal presence at event in exchange for attendee data-sharing agreement (Legal template required)"
    }
  ],
  "top_improvement": "Add a dedicated Anti-Patterns section with 5 role-specific failure modes — this role currently has zero anti-patterns, which is a disqualifying gap per the template standard and the single most likely cause of AI agent drift during unsupervised channel management tasks."
